<DOC><DOCNO> AP880419-0112 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-88 1136EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-GamblingIndictments     04-19 0218</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Gambling Indictments,0225</SECOND><HEAD>Mayor of Chicago Suburb, Two Others, Indicted in Alleged GamblingRing</HEAD><DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A suburban police chief's undercover activity forthe FBI has resulted in federal gambling indictments of the mayorand two other men, prosecutors say.   ``I've taken an oath to follow the law,'' Police Chief AntonGraff said on Monday, ``and I feel nobody is above the law, eventhe mayor.''   Mayor Kenneth Fisher of Dixmoor was charged Monday withconspiracy to commit racketeering, racketeering, lying to a federalagent and obstruction of justice, said Assistant U.S. AttorneySteven Miller.   The mayor was accused of taking bribes to allow a gamblingoperation in the town for five years, Miller said.   Benjamin Laster of Downers Grove and Samuel Perry of CalumetCity were indicted on charges of racketeering and conspiracy,prosecutors said.   Miller would not comment on the nature of the alleged gamblingoperation, but Graff said it was primarily bookmaking on horseraces.   The indictment said the operation was based at two taverns, oneof them owned by Laster.   Valukas called Graff the hero of the operation, saying thepolice chief was offered bribes by Laster to protect the gamblingoperation, but notified the FBI of the bribe attempt.   Graff began secretly working for the FBI in March 1986,officials said.</TEXT></DOC>